 family and friends to end off the work week. Details: The market will take place on January 25 at 44 Stanley Avenue, Braamfontein Werf, Johannesburg. The market takes place from 5pm to 9pm. For more information visit the 44 Stanley Facebook page. Telling Stories: Through the all-seeing eyes of men and women who live on the street, this play tells the story of pre- and post-apartheid South Africa. Each narrator challenges the audience to examine the cheap dream of freedom they have been sold. Details: The show will take place until January 27 at the POP Art Centre, 286 Fox Street, Johannesburg. Tickets cost R120 to R140. For more information, or to buy tickets, visit popartcentre.co.za Lala la by Simphiwe Buthelezi: In partnership with Blessing Ngobeni, the Bag Factory presents Lala la. Curated by Chumisa Ndakisa, the title of the show means “rest here” in isiZulu. The phrase is an offering of comfort. For Buthelezi, the body of work is a place where she has room to nurture, fix and right wrongs away from societal expectations. Details: The exhibition will take place until February 22 at the Bag Factory, 10 Mahlathini Street, Newtown, Johannesburg. For more information visit bagfactoryart.org.za Uncharted Lands and Trackless Seas by Simphiwe Ndzube:  Here the artist stages a make-believe plane titled Echoes of the First Stories with paintings, sculpture and audio interventions. His work draws from magical realism and the unknown with influences from people such as Zakes Mda, Ben Okri, David Lynch and Alejandro Jodorowsky. Details: The show opens on January 25 at Stevenson, 160 Sir Lowry Road, Woodstock, Cape Town. The artist will give a walkabout at 11am in support of the Friends of Iziko South African National Gallery. Tickets cost R80 for members, R100 for non-members and R25 for those aged 25 or younger. For more information visit stevenson.info Day and Night by Sarah Pratt: The artist imagines the unlikely friendship between birds, mammals and plants that are usually separated by habit, biology and habitat. Details: The exhibition, at Salon 91, 91 Kloof Street, Gardens, Cape Town, will end on February 23. For more information visit salon91.co.za Laughing Lines: Under the guidance of composer Hans Roosenschoon, Jesse Dreyer, Ibiayo Kayode and Conrad Asman created a musical piece focused on humour. This will be followed by a discussion regarding the creative process behind the performance with members of the Johannesburg Festival Orchestra. Details: The event takes place on January 26 at the Goethe-Institut, 119 Jan Smuts Avenue, Parkwood, Johannesburg. Entry is free. For more information visit goethe.de/johannesburg